Well that'll just be the trivial rotation, the rotation where you don't do anything.

234
00:22:06,320 --> 00:22:07,800
What about inverses?

235
00:22:07,800 --> 00:22:10,320
How do we invert a rotation?

236
00:22:10,320 --> 00:22:17,680
Well if a rotation involves rotating around some axis in the counterclockwise direction,

237
00:22:17,680 --> 00:22:23,280
then we can undo it just by rotating in the clockwise direction.

238
00:22:23,280 --> 00:22:29,680
So we can see that every rotation does indeed have an inverse.

239
00:22:29,680 --> 00:22:35,400
So that wraps up the explanation for how rotations form a mathematical group.

240
00:22:35,400 --> 00:22:39,520
This is a good opportunity for me to talk about matrices.

241
00:22:39,520 --> 00:22:44,320
Let's write the actual mathematical formula for the rotation around the x-axis by an angle

242
00:22:44,320 --> 00:22:46,320
of theta.

243
00:22:46,320 --> 00:22:51,640
We express the rotation as a transformation on a position vector.

244
00:22:51,640 --> 00:23:00,400
We can also write this as a 3x3 matrix acting on the original vector.

245
00:23:00,400 --> 00:23:05,400
To explain what distinguishes rotation matrices from any old arbitrary matrix, we have to

246
00:23:05,400 --> 00:23:08,080
discuss the inner product.

247
00:23:08,080 --> 00:23:11,760
Say you have two three-dimensional vectors r1 and r2.

248
00:23:11,760 --> 00:23:18,360
The inner product of r1 with r2, which can also be written as r1 transpose times r2,

249
00:23:18,360 --> 00:23:25,160
is equal to the sum of the products of their components.

250
00:23:25,160 --> 00:23:30,920
Geometrically, the inner product of two vectors is just the product of the lengths of the vectors

251
00:23:30,920 --> 00:23:34,400
times the cosine of the angle between them.

252
00:23:34,400 --> 00:23:40,160
Now notice that rotations preserve both lengths and relative angles.

253
00:23:40,160 --> 00:23:48,840
This means that if you rotate both vectors together, their inner product won't change.

254
00:23:48,840 --> 00:23:54,880
In other words, if we denote the rotation matrix with the letter uppercase r, then the inner

255
00:23:54,880 --> 00:24:02,040
product of uppercase r times r1 and uppercase r times r2 is equal to the inner product of

256
00:24:02,040 --> 00:24:04,480
r1 with r2.

257
00:24:04,480 --> 00:24:09,320
For this equation to hold for any choice of position vectors, we need for the transpose

258
00:24:09,320 --> 00:24:16,360
of the rotation matrix times itself to be equal to the identity matrix.

259
00:24:16,360 --> 00:24:21,240
When we have this condition, we say that the matrix is orthogonal.

260
00:24:21,240 --> 00:24:26,760
So we see that a matrix must be orthogonal if it represents a rotation.

261
00:24:27,520 --> 00:24:34,320
Now we call the group of all rotation matrices SO3.

262
00:24:34,320 --> 00:24:41,480
Here, the three just refers to the fact that the matrices are all three-dimensional.

263
00:24:41,480 --> 00:24:47,960
The O stands for orthogonal and the S stands for special, which means that all the matrices

264
00:24:47,960 --> 00:24:50,520
have determinant 1.

265
00:24:50,520 --> 00:24:54,680
This is just because we don't want any matrices that would flip the orientation of our axes

266
00:24:54,920 --> 00:24:58,560
and have determinant minus 1, but let's not get into that.

267
00:24:58,560 --> 00:25:04,800
So from here on out, whenever I say SO3, remember that I'm talking about the group of all rotations

268
00:25:04,800 --> 00:25:09,960
of three-dimensional space.

269
00:25:09,960 --> 00:25:13,880
One of the nice things about group theory is that, because the definition of a group

270
00:25:13,880 --> 00:25:18,360
is so general, it applies in many different situations.

271
00:25:18,360 --> 00:25:22,280
Here is another completely different example of a group.

272
00:25:22,360 --> 00:25:26,440
First, begin by choosing any topological space.

273
00:25:26,440 --> 00:25:31,800
For example, here is the two-dimensional torus, which we call T2.

274
00:25:31,800 --> 00:25:35,240
Note that this torus is hollow and isn't filled in.

275
00:25:35,240 --> 00:25:42,120
Next, choose one arbitrary point on the torus, which we will call the base point.

276
00:25:42,120 --> 00:25:47,400
Consider a path on the torus that starts and ends at this base point.

277
00:25:47,400 --> 00:25:51,640
Remember that you can imagine the path like a little monorail track with the train going

278
00:25:51,640 --> 00:25:53,720
around in one direction.

279
00:25:53,720 --> 00:25:58,840
Importantly, the path is directed, so if the train were to go around in the other direction,

280
00:25:58,840 --> 00:26:02,680
we would consider that a distinct path.

281
00:26:02,680 --> 00:26:08,440
Furthermore, we'll consider any two paths to be the same if they can be continuously

282
00:26:08,440 --> 00:26:12,040
deformed into one another.

283
00:26:13,960 --> 00:26:20,760
Finally, we define pi1 of T2, which we call the fundamental group of the torus,

284
00:26:20,760 --> 00:26:25,880
to be the set of all paths which start and end at the base point.

285
00:26:25,880 --> 00:26:29,880
Now, even though we used the explicit example of the torus,

286
00:26:29,880 --> 00:26:36,280
every topological space has its own associated fundamental group.

287
00:26:36,280 --> 00:26:42,120
Now, you may be asking, wait, how can we add two paths together?

288
00:26:42,120 --> 00:26:46,520
To answer that, let's look at a different topological space.

289
00:26:46,520 --> 00:26:52,120
Here we have a two-dimensional disc with two holes cut out of it.

290
00:26:52,120 --> 00:26:55,800
Now let's choose an arbitrary base point, as well as two paths,

291
00:26:55,800 --> 00:27:01,880
p1 and p2. Here is our little train going around the first path, p1,

292
00:27:01,880 --> 00:27:05,960
and here it is going around the second path, p2.

293
00:27:05,960 --> 00:27:12,520
Now, to define the path p1 plus p2, we just have the train go around p1,

294
00:27:12,520 --> 00:27:16,200
and then go around p2.

295
00:27:16,200 --> 00:27:21,400
We can continuously deform this path to get a better look at it.

296
00:27:22,120 --> 00:27:25,880
All right, so what then is the inverse of a path?

297
00:27:25,880 --> 00:27:29,560
Well, if here we have a path p where the train goes around

298
00:27:29,560 --> 00:27:33,080
in one direction, then negative p is the path

299
00:27:33,080 --> 00:27:37,640
where the train goes around in the other direction.

300
00:27:39,240 --> 00:27:44,200
The path p plus negative p can always be deformed to the trivial path,

301
00:27:44,200 --> 00:27:47,880
which is the identity element of the group.

302
00:27:52,760 --> 00:27:57,720
So now that we know what the fundamental group is, let me ask you a question.

303
00:27:57,720 --> 00:28:03,560
What is the fundamental group of SO3?

304
00:28:03,800 --> 00:28:07,000
Here we have a bit of groupception, because I'm asking

305
00:28:07,000 --> 00:28:11,480
what is the fundamental group of a group?

306
00:28:12,200 --> 00:28:16,360
Well, here's SO3. Remember, this is just our old friend,

307
00:28:16,360 --> 00:28:22,280
the space of rotations. I've put the base point right in the center.

308
00:28:22,280 --> 00:28:26,600
Now, here is the only non-trivial path in SO3,

309
00:28:26,600 --> 00:28:32,440
corresponding to the 2-pi twist. If we add this path to itself, we get the

310
00:28:32,440 --> 00:28:37,480
4-pi twist, which can be contracted to the identity.

311
00:28:38,200 --> 00:28:45,240
Therefore, p plus p equals id. We could also rephrase this as p

312
00:28:45,240 --> 00:28:49,640
equals negative p, which is just because p can be continuously deformed

313
00:28:49,640 --> 00:28:52,600
into its inverse.

314
00:28:57,320 --> 00:29:03,720
Therefore, the fundamental group of SO3 only has two elements.

315
00:29:04,200 --> 00:29:09,960
Here is the full table for how you can add these two elements together.

316
00:29:11,240 --> 00:29:17,080
This is the full description for the fundamental group of SO3.

317
00:29:17,080 --> 00:29:21,240
Now, if we symbolically replace id with zero

318
00:29:21,240 --> 00:29:27,960
and p with one, then this table begins to look a little familiar.

319
00:29:28,760 --> 00:29:31,960
Specifically, we can see that the fundamental group

320
00:29:31,960 --> 00:29:41,080
of SO3 is just the integer's modulo 2, also known as z mod 2.

321
00:29:42,680 --> 00:29:47,800
Think about all of the beautiful mathematics summed up in this equation.

322
00:29:47,800 --> 00:29:53,000
The whole Dirac belt trick is just a demonstration of the fact that the

323
00:29:53,000 --> 00:29:59,240
fundamental group of the space of rotations is z mod 2.

324
00:29:59,480 --> 00:30:04,040
Now, if you'll indulge me for a moment, I'd like to talk about what makes

325
00:30:04,040 --> 00:30:08,840
mathematics so non-trivial. SO3 is a good example of the kind of

326
00:30:08,840 --> 00:30:12,360
object you see in math. You can think of it as a group,

327
00:30:12,360 --> 00:30:17,080
and you can think of it as a topological space.

328
00:30:17,080 --> 00:30:20,120
Therefore, we can study it using group theory,

329
00:30:20,120 --> 00:30:24,600
or we can study it using topology. Often in mathematics,

330
00:30:24,600 --> 00:30:27,480
you start by thinking about an object in one way,

331
00:30:27,480 --> 00:30:31,880
and then discover you can think about it in a completely different way.

332
00:30:31,880 --> 00:30:35,880
And, crucially, all the different ways to think about an object

333
00:30:35,880 --> 00:30:40,600
interact with each other. So, the group theory has implications for the

334
00:30:40,600 --> 00:30:46,360
topology, and the topology has implications for the group theory.

335
00:30:47,560 --> 00:30:51,160
Let's give a summary of part three.

336
00:30:51,160 --> 00:30:57,320
A group is a set with an operation that satisfies a handful of rules.

337
00:30:57,320 --> 00:31:01,720
The set of rotations forms a group. Rotations can be expressed using

338
00:31:01,720 --> 00:31:05,080
matrices, and the group of rotation matrices is

339
00:31:05,080 --> 00:31:09,720
denoted SO3. Every topological space has a group

340
00:31:09,720 --> 00:31:13,080
associated with it, called its fundamental group,

341
00:31:13,080 --> 00:31:18,120
which is the set of paths which start and end at a base point.

342
00:31:18,120 --> 00:31:23,240
The fundamental group of SO3 is z mod 2.

343
00:31:27,960 --> 00:31:38,200
It's finally time to discuss spin in quantum mechanics.

344
00:31:38,200 --> 00:31:43,400
You're probably used to thinking of vectors with an x, y, and z component.

345
00:31:43,400 --> 00:31:47,320
Normally, we'd say that vectors are elements of the set R3,

346
00:31:47,320 --> 00:31:50,680
because they're comprised of three real numbers.

347
00:31:50,680 --> 00:31:53,640
However, quantum spin vectors are a little different.

348
00:31:53,640 --> 00:31:56,760
They're instead comprised of two complex numbers,

349
00:31:56,840 --> 00:31:59,720
where here alpha and beta are the complex numbers,

350
00:31:59,720 --> 00:32:04,440
and thus we say that they are elements of the set C2.

351
00:32:04,440 --> 00:32:08,440
Remember that a complex number can be written as a plus bi,

352
00:32:08,440 --> 00:32:11,640
where a is the real part and b is the imaginary part.

353
00:32:11,640 --> 00:32:15,240
We can also write it as r times e to the i theta,

354
00:32:15,240 --> 00:32:18,760
using Euler's formula to express it in terms of a

355
00:32:18,760 --> 00:32:24,120
magnitude r and an angle theta. The other thing about complex numbers is

356
00:32:24,120 --> 00:32:26,520
that they can be quote-unquote conjugated.

357
00:32:26,520 --> 00:32:32,840
So, for instance, the conjugate of alpha would be a minus bi.

358
00:32:32,840 --> 00:32:35,960
Finally, the absolute value squared of a complex number

359
00:32:35,960 --> 00:32:38,440
is just the number times its conjugate,

360
00:32:38,440 --> 00:32:45,160
which is equal to a squared plus b squared, also known as r squared.

361
00:32:45,160 --> 00:32:49,560
Now, what do these complex numbers correspond to in the physical world?

362
00:32:49,560 --> 00:32:53,240
Well, say you had an electron whose spin vector had the components

363
00:32:53,240 --> 00:32:57,560
of alpha and beta. If you measure the direction of the

364
00:32:57,560 --> 00:33:01,720
electron's spin along the z-axis, then the probability that you find

365
00:33:01,720 --> 00:33:06,360
it to be spin up will be the absolute value of alpha squared.

366
00:33:06,360 --> 00:33:09,720
Meanwhile, the probability that you find it to be spin down

367
00:33:09,720 --> 00:33:13,640
will be the absolute value of beta squared.

368
00:33:13,640 --> 00:33:17,560
So, for instance, the state with components one and zero

369
00:33:17,560 --> 00:33:20,840
will be measured to be spin up 100 percent of the time,

370
00:33:20,920 --> 00:33:24,760
while the state with components zero and one will be measured to be

371
00:33:24,760 --> 00:33:28,920
spin down 100 percent of the time.

372
00:33:31,720 --> 00:33:35,560
Notice that, because all probabilities must sum to one,

373
00:33:35,560 --> 00:33:39,640
the absolute value of alpha squared plus the absolute value of beta squared

374
00:33:39,640 --> 00:33:42,760
must be equal to one.

375
00:33:44,760 --> 00:33:49,480
Now, as we discussed previously, vectors in r3 have an inner product where you

376
00:33:49,480 --> 00:33:54,120
take the transpose of one vector and multiply it by the other.

377
00:33:54,120 --> 00:33:57,880
Quantum spin vectors, however, have an inner product where you take the

378
00:33:57,880 --> 00:34:03,960
conjugate transpose of one vector and then multiply it by the other.

379
00:34:05,000 --> 00:34:09,400
Just to be clear, in order to take the conjugate transpose of a spin vector,

380
00:34:09,400 --> 00:34:13,320
you just complex conjugate the components and turn the column vector

381
00:34:13,320 --> 00:34:16,360
into a row vector.

382
00:34:17,160 --> 00:34:21,080
Now, you can use this inner product in order to extract the components of these

383
00:34:21,080 --> 00:34:24,920
spin vectors. For instance, the inner product of one

384
00:34:24,920 --> 00:34:31,240
zero with alpha beta is just alpha. Likewise, the inner product of zero

385
00:34:31,240 --> 00:34:36,040
one with alpha beta is just beta.

386
00:34:37,640 --> 00:34:40,760
Therefore, the probability to measure an electron to be

387
00:34:40,760 --> 00:34:44,840
spin up with respect to the z-axis is the absolute value squared

388
00:34:44,840 --> 00:34:49,080
of the inner product of the spin up state with alpha beta.

389
00:34:49,080 --> 00:34:53,800
Likewise, the probability to be spin down with respect to the z-axis

390
00:34:53,800 --> 00:34:57,240
is the absolute value squared of the inner product of the spin

391
00:34:57,240 --> 00:35:00,760
down state with alpha beta.

392
00:35:03,800 --> 00:35:07,400
Now, there's nothing fundamentally special about the z-axis.

393
00:35:07,400 --> 00:35:11,880
Here, I'll write the spin up and down states with respect to the x-axis

394
00:35:11,880 --> 00:35:18,280
and y-axis as well. So, the probability of a state to be, say,

395
00:35:18,280 --> 00:35:22,600
measured spin down along the y-axis will be the absolute value squared

396
00:35:22,600 --> 00:35:27,400
of the inner product of the spin down y-state with alpha beta.

397
00:35:27,400 --> 00:35:31,720
And likewise, you would have the same thing for being, say, spin up along the x-axis

398
00:35:31,720 --> 00:35:34,520
or what have you.

399
00:35:37,240 --> 00:35:40,200
So, whereas the inner product of position vectors

400
00:35:40,200 --> 00:35:44,360
is used to find lengths and angles, the inner product of our complex two

401
00:35:44,360 --> 00:35:50,600
dimensional spin vectors is used to find the probabilities of measurements.

402
00:35:51,960 --> 00:35:55,160
Now, we can also use the inner product to re-express

403
00:35:55,160 --> 00:35:59,160
another equation that we've seen. Remember that the condition that

404
00:35:59,160 --> 00:36:03,320
probabilities must sum to one implies that the absolute value of alpha

405
00:36:03,320 --> 00:36:07,400
squared plus the absolute value of beta squared must be equal to one.

406
00:36:07,400 --> 00:36:11,240
This is equivalent to saying that the inner product of a spin vector

407
00:36:11,240 --> 00:36:15,880
with itself must be equal to one. When we have this condition,

408
00:36:15,880 --> 00:36:19,880
we say that our spin vector is properly normalized or that we have a

409
00:36:19,880 --> 00:36:22,680
physical state.

410
00:36:26,040 --> 00:36:29,960
Now, let's talk about rotations. As we discussed earlier,

411
00:36:29,960 --> 00:36:34,040
rotations act on vectors as three by three matrices.

412
00:36:34,040 --> 00:36:38,360
In order to rotate a spin vector, however, we'll instead have to use a two

413
00:36:38,360 --> 00:36:42,920
by two matrix with complex entries. We'll label this matrix with the

414
00:36:42,920 --> 00:36:46,920
letter u. Remember that our rotation matrix

415
00:36:46,920 --> 00:36:50,440
needed to satisfy the condition that the transpose of the matrix

416
00:36:50,440 --> 00:36:53,960
times the matrix itself must be equal to the identity.

417
00:36:53,960 --> 00:36:59,320
What is the analogous condition that this new matrix u must satisfy?

418
00:37:00,200 --> 00:37:06,520
First off, rotating a spin vector shouldn't change the inner product of it

419
00:37:06,520 --> 00:37:09,640
with itself. Because if that starts off as one, then it

420
00:37:09,640 --> 00:37:15,080
should remain one after being rotated. In order for this to hold, we must have

421
00:37:15,080 --> 00:37:19,240
that the conjugate transpose of u times u

422
00:37:19,240 --> 00:37:23,720
is equal to the identity matrix. When we have this condition,

423
00:37:23,720 --> 00:37:28,520
we say that u is a unitary matrix.

424
00:37:31,400 --> 00:37:35,560
Now, aside from being unitary, there's one other slightly technical condition

425
00:37:35,560 --> 00:37:40,280
that we need to put on u. First, note that the spin vectors with the

426
00:37:40,280 --> 00:37:44,280
components of alpha, beta, and e to the i theta alpha,

427
00:37:44,280 --> 00:37:48,600
e to the i theta beta, have no observable differences.

428
00:37:48,600 --> 00:37:52,200
So, for example, when calculating the probability

429
00:37:52,200 --> 00:37:55,800
that the second state is spin up along the z-axis,

430
00:37:55,800 --> 00:37:59,080
the e to the i theta makes no difference in the final answer,

431
00:37:59,080 --> 00:38:03,880
because you're just taking the absolute value squared of that inner product.

432
00:38:03,880 --> 00:38:06,920
Physicists tend to call this factor of e to the i theta

433
00:38:06,920 --> 00:38:12,280
a phase. Anyway, this implies that the matrix u

434
00:38:12,280 --> 00:38:18,760
and e to the i theta times u correspond to the exact same transformation.

435
00:38:18,760 --> 00:38:22,120
Therefore, to get rid of this redundancy, we can choose

436
00:38:22,120 --> 00:38:26,280
for the determinant of u to be equal to one.

437
00:38:26,280 --> 00:38:29,720
Finally, we denote the set of all such matrices u

438
00:38:29,720 --> 00:38:35,960
that satisfy these conditions as su2. The two refers to the fact that the

439
00:38:35,960 --> 00:38:39,560
matrices are two-dimensional, the u refers to the fact that they're

440
00:38:39,560 --> 00:38:43,880
unitary, and the s stands for special, which means that the matrices have

441
00:38:43,880 --> 00:38:46,440
determinant one.

442
00:38:50,040 --> 00:38:56,680
So, to summarize part four, quantum spin states are vectors in c2.

443
00:38:56,680 --> 00:39:00,360
The inner product of spin vectors involves taking the conjugate transpose

444
00:39:00,360 --> 00:39:04,360
of one vector and multiplying it by the second one.

445
00:39:04,360 --> 00:39:07,720
There are states which are always spin up or spin down

446
00:39:07,720 --> 00:39:11,160
when measured with respect to certain directions in space.

447
00:39:11,160 --> 00:39:14,600
The probability that a state will be spin up in some direction

448
00:39:14,600 --> 00:39:18,520
will be the absolute value squared of its inner product with the spin up

449
00:39:18,520 --> 00:39:21,800
vector. In order to rotate a spin state, you

450
00:39:21,800 --> 00:39:27,080
must act on it by a matrix u in su2.

451
00:39:27,320 --> 00:39:41,960
Earlier, we got acquainted with s03 as a topological space.

452
00:39:41,960 --> 00:39:45,400
So, what about su2?

453
00:39:47,160 --> 00:39:50,280
Well, first let's write the 2 by 2 matrix u

454
00:39:50,280 --> 00:39:54,440
and call its four entries a, b, c, and d.

455
00:39:54,440 --> 00:39:57,800
Now, remember that u conjugate transpose times u

456
00:39:57,800 --> 00:40:02,680
must be equal to the identity matrix. This is equivalent to saying that u

457
00:40:02,680 --> 00:40:07,320
conjugate transpose must be equal to u inverse.

458
00:40:07,320 --> 00:40:11,560
If we write out this equation explicitly

459
00:40:11,560 --> 00:40:17,080
and use the fact that the determinant of u is equal to one,

460
00:40:17,080 --> 00:40:20,680
then after staring at this verbit, we realize that d

461
00:40:20,680 --> 00:40:24,840
must be equal to the conjugate of a, and c must be equal to

462
00:40:24,840 --> 00:40:29,080
minus the conjugate of b. Plugging these equations back in,

463
00:40:29,080 --> 00:40:32,680
we see that u must have the entries of a, b,

464
00:40:32,680 --> 00:40:38,040
negative b conjugate, and a conjugate. Now, notice that the determinant of this

465
00:40:38,040 --> 00:40:41,160
matrix is equal to the absolute value of a squared

466
00:40:41,160 --> 00:40:45,240
plus the absolute value of b squared. If we write

467
00:40:45,240 --> 00:40:51,000
a equals x plus i, y, and b equals z plus i, w,

468
00:40:51,000 --> 00:40:54,280
then the condition that this matrix has determinant one

469
00:40:54,280 --> 00:40:58,600
becomes x squared plus y squared plus z squared plus w squared

470
00:40:58,600 --> 00:41:03,160
equals one. So, this is all just to say that a completely

471
00:41:03,160 --> 00:41:07,240
general su2 matrix can be given by four real numbers

472
00:41:07,240 --> 00:41:11,880
x, y, z, and w such that x squared plus y squared plus z squared plus w

473
00:41:11,880 --> 00:41:16,440
squared equals one. This is the equation for something called

474
00:41:16,440 --> 00:41:21,320
the three sphere, which we denote s3.

475
00:41:27,320 --> 00:41:32,120
How do we picture this three sphere? Well, you might be familiar with the two

476
00:41:32,120 --> 00:41:35,480
sphere, which is given by the equation x squared plus y

477
00:41:35,480 --> 00:41:40,760
squared plus z squared equals one. The two sphere, which is hollow much

478
00:41:40,760 --> 00:41:44,360
like a beach ball, can be embedded in three-dimensional space,

479
00:41:44,360 --> 00:41:48,920
which allows us to easily visualize it. The three sphere,

480
00:41:48,920 --> 00:41:52,600
on the other hand, is embedded in four-dimensional space,

481
00:41:52,600 --> 00:41:56,120
which makes it much harder to picture. However,

482
00:41:56,120 --> 00:42:00,280
there is something we can do. Let's look again at the two sphere.

483
00:42:00,280 --> 00:42:03,960
You can divide it into two halves along the equator.

484
00:42:03,960 --> 00:42:08,040
You can then cut the sphere, flatten out the two pieces,

485
00:42:08,040 --> 00:42:12,440
and get two discs. These discs can be thought of as

486
00:42:12,440 --> 00:42:15,880
the set of points with x squared plus y squared

487
00:42:15,880 --> 00:42:20,200
less than or equal to one in the 2D plane.

488
00:42:20,200 --> 00:42:25,000
Anyway, let's refer to these discs as sheets.

489
00:42:27,400 --> 00:42:32,440
Here's a side-by-side view of the sphere and its two sheets.

490
00:42:32,440 --> 00:42:35,560
We can see what it looks like for a point to move around on the sphere

491
00:42:35,560 --> 00:42:38,920
from the perspective of the sheets.

492
00:42:41,480 --> 00:42:44,600
Notice that when the point hits the boundary of one sheet,

493
00:42:44,600 --> 00:42:47,880
it emerges on the other sheet.

494
00:42:52,760 --> 00:42:56,360
Therefore, we can see that the two sphere is equivalent to

495
00:42:56,360 --> 00:43:01,080
two different discs glued along their boundary.

496
00:43:01,240 --> 00:43:08,600
Now we can return to the three sphere. By direct analogy, the three sphere can be

497
00:43:08,600 --> 00:43:12,360
pictured as two solid balls which are glued together along

498
00:43:12,360 --> 00:43:16,520
their boundary. If a point hits the boundary of one

499
00:43:16,520 --> 00:43:20,360
ball, it will emerge on the other.

500
00:43:21,000 --> 00:43:25,720
Once again, we will refer to each ball as a sheet.

501
00:43:25,720 --> 00:43:30,360
So how is this three sphere related to SO3?

502
00:43:30,360 --> 00:43:33,640
Well, to discuss that, I'll need to introduce the concept

503
00:43:33,640 --> 00:43:40,200
of a covering space. Here I have an example of a covering space

504
00:43:40,200 --> 00:43:46,200
and a base space. In this example, the base space is just a circle and the

505
00:43:46,200 --> 00:43:52,920
covering space is also a circle, but it's been sort of doubled over on itself.

506
00:43:52,920 --> 00:43:56,760
Every point in the covering space can be projected down

507
00:43:56,760 --> 00:44:01,640
to a point in the base space. In this example, the projection map is a

508
00:44:01,640 --> 00:44:04,760
two-to-one function.

509
00:44:05,960 --> 00:44:09,640
But instead, what if we want to take a point in the base space

510
00:44:09,640 --> 00:44:13,880
and lift it to a point in the covering space?

511
00:44:13,880 --> 00:44:18,840
Well, now there are two possible choices for a point we could lift it to.

512
00:44:18,840 --> 00:44:25,080
Let's just choose the bottom point. Now let's see what happens if we move the

513
00:44:25,080 --> 00:44:28,520
point in the base space around in a loop and then bring it back to its

514
00:44:28,520 --> 00:44:31,400
original position.

515
00:44:35,000 --> 00:44:39,640
Interesting, so even though we initially decided to lift to the bottom

516
00:44:39,640 --> 00:44:43,000
choice, when we moved around in a loop, we were

517
00:44:43,000 --> 00:44:46,840
forced to end up with the top choice.

518
00:44:47,560 --> 00:44:52,200
Therefore, when we try to lift paths from the base space to the

519
00:44:52,200 --> 00:44:56,360
covering space, sometimes the start point and the end point of the path

520
00:44:56,360 --> 00:44:59,960
won't be the same in the covering space, even though they were the same in the

521
00:44:59,960 --> 00:45:02,520
base space.

522
00:45:03,320 --> 00:45:07,000
Now we are finally able to describe the relationship

523
00:45:07,000 --> 00:45:14,920
between SU2 and SO3. SU2 is the covering space of SO3.

524
00:45:14,920 --> 00:45:18,360
Just as in our example, this is a two-to-one covering,

525
00:45:18,360 --> 00:45:22,360
which we call a double cover.

526
00:45:23,080 --> 00:45:26,840
Just to get acquainted, let's see what happens when we move around a point

527
00:45:26,840 --> 00:45:29,640
in the base space.

528
00:45:30,360 --> 00:45:47,400
Now let's see what happens when we try to lift the path

529
00:45:47,400 --> 00:45:51,320
corresponding to the two-pi twist.

530
00:45:53,320 --> 00:45:57,960
Notice that in the covering space SU2, the start point of the path is

531
00:45:57,960 --> 00:46:01,560
different from the end point of the path.

532
00:46:10,200 --> 00:46:13,560
Interestingly, you could use this fact to rigorously prove

533
00:46:13,560 --> 00:46:17,960
that the two-pi twist is non-contractable in SO3.

534
00:46:17,960 --> 00:46:23,640
The proof follows by contradiction. If you could contract the path in SO3 to

535
00:46:23,640 --> 00:46:27,480
the trivial path, then you could also continuously lift the

536
00:46:27,480 --> 00:46:32,280
quote-unquote movie of the contraction to the covering space.

537
00:46:32,280 --> 00:46:36,200
This would then get you a contraction of the lifted path as well.

538
00:46:36,200 --> 00:46:39,640
However, because the start point in the covering space

539
00:46:39,640 --> 00:46:42,600
is different from the end point in the covering space,

540
00:46:42,600 --> 00:46:45,480
and because the start point and end point will always stay

541
00:46:45,480 --> 00:46:49,720
anchored in their positions during this movie, then clearly we can't contract the

542
00:46:49,720 --> 00:46:53,720
path in the covering space. Therefore, the path in the base space

543
00:46:53,720 --> 00:46:59,640
must be non-contractable as well, which is exactly what we wanted to prove.

544
00:47:02,280 --> 00:47:06,920
Actually, this proof is just one aspect of a more general phenomenon

545
00:47:06,920 --> 00:47:09,800
where non-contractable paths in a base space

546
00:47:09,800 --> 00:47:15,640
lift to paths which start and end at different points in a covering space.

547
00:47:16,200 --> 00:47:23,000
To finish up this part of the video, let me just show you how the

548
00:47:23,000 --> 00:47:31,560
four-pi twist can be contracted just for kicks.

549
00:47:32,440 --> 00:47:45,960
Let's now give a summary of part five.

