551
00:47:53,400 --> 00:47:59,000
glued along their boundaries, which you could also think of as the equator.

552
00:47:59,080 --> 00:48:05,640
SU2 is a double cover of SO3. If you lift the path corresponding to the

553
00:48:05,640 --> 00:48:10,440
two-pi twist in SO3 to SU2, then the start point

554
00:48:10,440 --> 00:48:13,720
and the end point of the path will not be the same.

555
00:48:13,720 --> 00:48:17,160
This fact can be used to prove that the two-pi twist

556
00:48:17,160 --> 00:48:28,840
is non-contractable in SO3.

557
00:48:29,800 --> 00:48:37,480
At the start of this video, I said that rotating an electron 360 degrees

558
00:48:37,480 --> 00:48:41,640
puts it in a negated version of its original state.

559
00:48:41,640 --> 00:48:44,680
Let's now synthesize all the math we've learned

560
00:48:44,680 --> 00:48:49,720
in order to understand how this statement actually makes sense.

561
00:48:49,720 --> 00:48:54,520
The group which acts on C2 spin vectors is SU2.

562
00:48:54,520 --> 00:48:58,600
Therefore, to rotate an electron, we must lift a path

563
00:48:58,600 --> 00:49:05,640
from SO3 to SU2. SU2 is a double cover of SO3,

564
00:49:05,640 --> 00:49:09,720
and the two-pi twist ends up at a different element of SU2

565
00:49:09,720 --> 00:49:15,960
than it started. More specifically, if we start the lifted path at the identity

566
00:49:15,960 --> 00:49:18,760
matrix,

567
00:49:18,760 --> 00:49:26,440
then it'll end up at negative the identity matrix.

568
00:49:26,440 --> 00:49:29,800
However, the four-pi twist does end where it starts

569
00:49:29,800 --> 00:49:32,440
in SU2.

570
00:49:38,440 --> 00:49:41,720
Therefore, rotating an electron by two-pi

571
00:49:41,720 --> 00:49:45,880
negates its spin vector while rotating it by four-pi

572
00:49:45,960 --> 00:49:52,440
returns it to its original state. So that completes the explanation.

573
00:49:52,440 --> 00:49:56,760
Just to write down some explicit equations, let me explain how to find the

574
00:49:56,760 --> 00:50:01,560
SO3 rotation matrix corresponding to a matrix in SU2.

575
00:50:01,560 --> 00:50:05,720
Start by taking a position vector, r equals xyz,

576
00:50:05,720 --> 00:50:09,080
and convert it into the following two-by-two matrix,

577
00:50:09,080 --> 00:50:13,880
r dot the polymatrices, which is just x times the first polymatrix

578
00:50:13,880 --> 00:50:18,760
plus y times the second polymatrix plus z times the third polymatrix.

579
00:50:18,760 --> 00:50:21,720
This is actually the most general form for a traceless

580
00:50:21,720 --> 00:50:25,720
self-adjoint two-by-two matrix. Furthermore, the determinant of this

581
00:50:25,720 --> 00:50:29,480
matrix is equal to x squared plus y squared plus z squared,

582
00:50:29,480 --> 00:50:34,520
which is just the length squared of r. If we multiply this matrix by u on the

583
00:50:34,520 --> 00:50:37,960
left and the conjugate transpose of u on the right,

584
00:50:37,960 --> 00:50:42,040
the overall matrix will still be traceless and self-adjoint.

585
00:50:42,040 --> 00:50:45,480
Furthermore, its determinant will be unchanged.

586
00:50:45,480 --> 00:50:49,560
Therefore, we can write this new matrix as a new position vector,

587
00:50:49,560 --> 00:50:53,640
which we call r prime, dotted with the polymatrices.

588
00:50:53,640 --> 00:50:56,680
Because r and r prime must have the same length,

589
00:50:56,680 --> 00:51:01,320
r prime must just be a rotated version of r.

590
00:51:01,320 --> 00:51:06,600
So the rotation matrix, uppercase r, is just whatever three-by-three matrix

591
00:51:06,600 --> 00:51:10,520
satisfies the equation r prime equals uppercase r

592
00:51:10,520 --> 00:51:15,240
times r. This is how you convert an SU2 matrix u

593
00:51:15,240 --> 00:51:22,440
into an SO3 matrix r. Now notice that u and negative u

594
00:51:22,440 --> 00:51:26,440
map to the exact same rotation.

595
00:51:27,160 --> 00:51:30,680
This is how we can see that SU2 really is a double cover

596
00:51:30,680 --> 00:51:33,400
of SO3.

597
00:51:34,200 --> 00:51:37,720
Finally, I should just mention that there's this really useful explicit

598
00:51:37,720 --> 00:51:42,520
formula for the SU2 matrix u corresponding to a rotation

599
00:51:42,520 --> 00:51:45,720
given an axis n hat and an angle of rotation

600
00:51:45,720 --> 00:51:51,160
theta. Namely, u equals cosine of theta over 2

601
00:51:51,160 --> 00:51:55,080
times the identity matrix plus sine of theta over 2

602
00:51:55,080 --> 00:52:00,040
times negative i n hat dot the polymatrices.

603
00:52:00,040 --> 00:52:05,000
Notice that if we plug in theta equals 2 pi, then u equals negative the identity

604
00:52:05,000 --> 00:52:08,600
matrix, meaning a 2 pi rotation does negate the spin

605
00:52:08,600 --> 00:52:12,840
vector of an electron. We can also write this using matrix

606
00:52:12,840 --> 00:52:15,640
exponentiation, but let's not get into that.

607
00:52:15,640 --> 00:52:19,640
Oof, glad I got that out of my chest.

